Vergil, however, does not write of real chephcrds, but introduces himself and his friends in the guise of shepherds, talking of the matters which concerned them, not of the themes which would naturally form the conversation of real shepherds In a word, the pastoral form is merely a pictur- esque setting for the poet’s ideas, not a reality.
